The paper presents a system that uses neural networks for perception, program generation, and program execution to learn human-readable plans from real-world demonstrations. The system is tested on the pick-and-place problem using a Baxter robot, indicating a focus on robotics (cs.RO). The perception network uses convolutional pose machines to detect objects in real images, indicating a focus on computer vision (cs.CV). The use of neural networks for program generation and execution suggests a focus on artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and machine learning (cs.LG). Finally, the system is designed to work in a simulated environment before being tested in the real world, indicating a focus on systems and control (cs.SY).
